    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3533847992" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3533847992" />
    <a title="gage sugden" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/90393527-gage-sugden"><img alt="gage sugden" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1635302619p2/90393527.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3533847992?book_show_action=true">Sep 25, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="gage sugden" class="user" itemprop="url" name="gage sugden" href="/user/show/90393527-gage-sugden">gage sugden</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3533847992" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer762527589595914324">Provocative and fascinating, Lenin clarifies (from his POV) many aspects left vague in the Manifesto. While at times (especially the 6th and final chapter) too specifically directed at rival theoretician Kautsky, it&apos;s general enough to be useful as more than just a historical document. It&apos;ll challenge how you think about the State (and nationality), whether you agree with Lenin&apos;s take or not.<br/><br/>That&apos;s probably the most interesting part. There&apos;s some dialectics here explaining the necessity for a re</span>
  <span id="freeText762527589595914324" style="display:none">Provocative and fascinating, Lenin clarifies (from his POV) many aspects left vague in the Manifesto. While at times (especially the 6th and final chapter) too specifically directed at rival theoretician Kautsky, it's general enough to be useful as more than just a historical document. It'll challenge how you think about the State (and nationality), whether you agree with Lenin's take or not.<br /><br />That's probably the most interesting part. There's some dialectics here explaining the necessity for a revolution and what that process will look like. There's a lot of explaining what Marxism isn't, which actually is a tremendously helpful way of learning what it is. Some of the best explanations of how Marxism isn't Utopianism as well as how the 'withering away of the state' will look. Explanation for how to do away with bureaucracy is fun cause it seems plausible but obviously Lenin didn't take his own advice when he got in charge. Interesting thoughts about incentive to work under first stage communism too - I wonder what Lenin would think about UBI. Lastly a great explanation of phrase 'from each according to his ability; to each according to his need' and generally on the topic of equality that is lightyears ahead of his time.<br /><br />There are other areas that are less convincing, such as his take on religion and the idea that the 'bookkeeping' that will keep the world running can be done by anyone - and he stresses multiple times he means literally anyone. I don't know if that was true 100 years ago, but I'm skeptical it's true now.<br /><br />While this book in addition to the other materials I've been reading I've found very convincing both philosophically and practically, there are still a couple aspects like this that make me question how useful Marxism can be today in the post-industrial world.<br /><br />I'd recommend to anyone who's read Manifesto or other beginning text. This book won't serve as an intro but is accessible and elucidating once you have the basics down.<br /><br />For now I'll keep on reading these primary texts, though I think (sooner rather than later) I'll have to read some modern work to really make my mind up on whether or not I actually buy Marxism in the 21st century.</span>
  <a data-text-id="762527589595914324" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


